To execute a procedure specified by a ProcHandle object, invoke the Call method defined for the ProcHandle class. Here is an example:

```
prochandle = CurSession.Scope.GetProcHandle(Name = 'appname!procname');
prochandle.Call(parameters);
```
In this example, `appname` must reference a directly included application where the procedure with the name `procname` is defined. The Call method uses the scope specified by the ProcHandle object to execute it.

You can write a field script that defines its own local cleanup procedures. In its initialize block it could insert its handles into an array of cleanup procedure handles defined at the frame level. Later, at cleanup time, the frame can loop through the cleanup array and use the handle to call each procedure:
```4gl
dim my_cleanup_procs[] as ProcHandle;

on init do
  // create local cleanup procedures
  my_cleanup_procs[0] = ... ; // insert handle of first cleanup procedure
  my_cleanup_procs[1] = ... ; // insert handle of second cleanup procedure
end on;

// at cleanup time, call each cleanup procedure using its ProcHandle object
foreach i in 0 to ubound(my_cleanup_procs) do
    my_cleanup_procs[i].Call();
end foreach;
```

Here's a sample field script that defines a local cleanup procedure and inserts its handle into an array of cleanup procedure handles defined at the frame level:

```
define script cleanup_script

    local procedure my_cleanup;
    export my_cleanup_handle as type(procHandle);

    initialize block
        // Define the local cleanup procedure "my_cleanup"
        procedure my_cleanup as void
            begin
                // Cleanup code for your script goes here.
            end;

        // Get the handle of the "my_cleanup" procedure and store it in a variable "my_cleanup_handle".
        my_cleanup_handle = CurFrame.Scope.GetProcHandle(name='my_cleanup');

        // Insert the cleanup handle into an array defined at the frame level.
        frame_cleanup_handles[array_index++] = my_cleanup_handle;
    end initialize block;

end define script;
```

To create an array of ProcHandle objects, you can define a variable as an array with the `dim` statement and then use the `GetProcHandle` method to populate it with handles for local cleanup procedures. Here is an example:
```
dim cleanup_procs[10];
cleanup_procs[1] = CurScriptScope.GetProcHandle('cleanup_proc1');
cleanup_procs[2] = CurFrame.Scope.GetProcHandle('cleanup_proc2');
...
```
Once you have created the array, you can use it to manage cleanup procedures by looping through the array and calling each procedure using the `Call` method defined for the ProcHandle class at cleanup time:
```
foreach proc in cleanup_procs do
    proc.Call();
end;
```
This way, all local cleanup procedures are called automatically at the appropriate time.
